From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}.<ref name="NKDc">{{R:ja:NKD Concise}}</ref>

Listed as the noun derivation of verb {{m|ja|йҺ§гҒҶ|tr=yorou||to put on, to equip oneself with}},<ref name="DDJS">{{R:Digital-Daijisen}}</ref><ref name="DJR"/><ref name="SMK5"/> which in turn appears to be the ''-o'' stem variant of the {{m|ja|жңӘз„¶еҪў|tr=mizenkei||irrealis verb conjugation form}} of verb {{m|ja|зё’гӮӢ|tr=yoru||to twist, plait, or spin together {{q|as thread or yarn}}; to tie on, to tie together {{q|as a collection of pieces}}}} + the classical iterative / repetitive / stative aspect verb suffix {{ja-r|гҒө|id=auxiliary}}, effectively meaning "to be tying together" as a verb, and thus something like "that which is tied together" as the derivative noun.  Notably, tying various kinds of [[cordage]] was an integral part of how traditional Japanese armor was worn.

That said, the noun is attested already in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 {{CE}},<ref name="NKDc"/> whereas the verb might not be attested until ''{{w|The Tale of the Heike}}'' of roughly 1330,<ref name="NDKc-yorou">{{R:ja:NKD Concise|йҺ§гҒҶ}}</ref> some four centuries later.  Then again, poem 2 in the ''{{w|Man'yЕҚshЕ«}}'' of 759 {{CE}} does include what may be this same verb spelled phonetically in {{w|man'yЕҚgana}} as {{m|ojp||иҲҮе‘Ӯеёғ|tr=yoвӮӮropu}},<ref name="NKDc-yoropu">{{R:ja:NKD Concise|гӮҲгӮҚгҒҶ}}</ref><ref name="MYS">{{RQ:MYS|1|2}}</ref> of uncertain meaning but possibly something like "to avail oneself of; to be to hand; to be equipped with".<ref name="NKDc-toriyoropu">{{R:ja:NKD Concise|гҒЁгӮҠгӮҲгӮҚгҒҶ}}</ref>

